          "body": "Woven between the idol-descriptions are four doxological counter-movements that build the chapter's positive case. 'There is none like You, O LORD' (10:6) is not merely a hymn fragment; it is a comparative claim: among all the wise men of all kingdoms, there is no one who can be compared to Yahweh (10:7). The climactic statement comes at 10:10 with three ontological predicates: He is the *true* God (emet — He corresponds to reality, He is not fictitious), the *living* God (chay — He possesses life in Himself, not manufactured), and the *everlasting* King (melekh olam — His reign has no terminus). At His wrath the earth quakes; nations cannot endure His indignation. Then the cosmological argument clinches it (10:12-13): the God who made the earth by power, established the world by wisdom, and stretched out the heavens by understanding is the same God who commands clouds from the ends of the earth and releases wind from His storehouses. Calvin noted that Jeremiah deliberately catalogues the phenomena the nations were most tempted to fear — signs of the heavens (10:2), storms, celestial events — and assigns them all to Yahweh's personal governance. The appropriate response to every omen is therefore not terror at the sign but fear of the One who commands it."
